`app/blog/[id]/page.tsx` - Server Component with data fetching
`app/blog/[id]/back-button.tsx` - Client component for the back button
`app/blog/[id]/loading.tsx` - Loading state (replaces `router.isFallback`)

### 5. API Routes

For `pages/api/posts/index.js` → `app/api/posts/route.ts`:
- GET handler returns posts array
- POST handler creates a post
- Other methods → 405

For `pages/api/posts/[id].js` → `app/api/posts/[id]/route.ts`:
- GET returns single post
- PUT updates post
- DELETE deletes post
- Other methods → 405

In App Router Route Handlers:
```typescript
export async function GET(request: NextRequest) { ... }
export async function POST(request: NextRequest) { ... }
```

The `req.body` in Pages Router becomes `await request.json()` in App Router.
The `req.query` becomes the `params` argument in the handler.
The `res.status().json()` becomes `NextResponse.json(data, { status })`.

### 6. `app/error.tsx` (replaces `_error.js`)

In App Router, `error.tsx` is a client component that catches errors in the segment and its children.

```tsx
'use client';

export default function Error({
  error,
  reset,
}: {
  error: Error & { digest?: string };
  reset: () => void;
}) {
  return (
    <div className="error-page">
      <h1>Something went wrong!</h1>
      <p>{error.message || 'An unexpected error occurred.'}</p>
      <button onClick={() => reset()}>Try again</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

The old `_error.js` had `getInitialProps` which is a legacy Pages Router API. In App Router, error handling is done through `error.tsx` and `global-error.tsx`.

